Blessed, who deals kindly with the world!/PR


Blessed are you!/PI/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. /ITBaruh/± Sheòamar/XX. Our morning psalm service begins with
the words "Blessed is the one who spoke." We begin to pray by proclaim-
ing the divinity and great power of words themselves. The prayerbook
conveys our sense of inadequacy of coming before God with human lan-
guage. How can words ever be adequate vehicles for expressing our most
inward thoughts?/PR

/SC/XXA.G./XX/PR

/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. The God affirmed in the words of /ITBaruh/± Sheòamar/XX may be
understood in either concrete anthropomorphic terms or in a more abstract
manner. It is the latter view with which we Reconstructionists are most
comfortable. Our God is not a person who promises and fulfills as a
human being would. In speaking of a God who fulfills promises, we
express our basic trust in life and our affirmation that goodness and godli-
ness have their own reward.    /SC/XXA.G./XX/PR

